# 🛡️ ASA — Attack Surface Analyzer

> Scan your own repo for secrets, vulnerable dependencies, misconfigurations and exposed endpoints — before you push to prod.

![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.9%2B-blue?logo=python)
![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-green)
![CI](https://github.com/your-username/attack-surface-analyzer/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg)

ASA is a developer-focused security CLI that runs locally on your project. No external service, no sign-up, no telemetry. It sits in the niche between DevSecOps tooling and offensive reconnaissance — helping you find what an attacker would find, before they do.

---

## ✨ Features

| Scanner | What it detects |
|---|---|
| 📦 **CVE / Dependencies** | Vulnerable packages via [OSV.dev](https://osv.dev) — supports `requirements.txt`, `pyproject.toml`, `Pipfile.lock`, `package.json`, `go.mod` |
| ⚙️ **Misconfigurations** | Dockerfile pitfalls, docker-compose risks, GitHub Actions supply-chain issues, weak `.env` values, nginx/SSL misconfigs |
| 🔑 **Hardcoded Secrets** | AWS keys, GitHub tokens, Stripe/Slack/OpenAI API keys, private PEM keys, DB connection strings with credentials, and more |
| 🌐 **Endpoint Exposure** | Admin/debug routes, CORS wildcards, Flask debug mode, Swagger/GraphQL without auth, docker socket mounts |

---

## 🚀 Quick Start

```bash
pip install attack-surface-analyzer
asa .
```

Or scan a specific project:

```bash
asa /path/to/my-project
```

Generate an HTML report:

```bash
asa . --html report.html
```

